WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:19.660
Part 2 of The Strange Case of Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde by Robert Louis Stevenson.

00:21.800 --> 00:25.420
THE CARILL MURDER CASE

00:25.420 --> 00:33.300
Nearly a year later, in the month of October, London was startled by a crime of singular ferocity,

00:33.720 --> 00:37.180
and rendered all the more notable by the high position of the victim.

00:38.000 --> 00:44.840
The details were few and startling. A maidservant, living alone in a house not far from the river,

00:45.220 --> 00:51.200
had gone upstairs to bed about eleven. Although a fog rolled over the city in small hours,

00:51.200 --> 00:56.760
the early part of the night was cloudless, and the lane, which the maid's window overlooked,

00:57.280 --> 01:04.940
was brilliantly lit by the full moon. It seems she was romantically given, for she sat down

01:04.940 --> 01:11.180
upon her box, which stood immediately under the window, and fell into a dream of musing.

01:11.920 --> 01:16.720
Never, she used to say, with streaming tears when she narrated that experience,

01:16.720 --> 01:22.660
never had she felt more at peace with all men, nor thought more kindly of the world.

01:23.740 --> 01:29.800
And as she so sat, she became aware of an aged, beautiful gentleman with white hair,

01:30.200 --> 01:36.600
drawing near along the lane, and advancing to meet him another and very small gentleman,

01:36.980 --> 01:42.940
to whom at first she paid less attention. When they had come within speech,

01:42.940 --> 01:49.780
which was just under the maid's eyes, the older man bowed, and accosted the other with a very

01:49.780 --> 01:56.340
pretty manner of politeness. It did not seem as if the subject of his address were of great importance.

01:57.020 --> 02:02.600
Indeed, from his pointing, it sometimes appeared as if he were only inquiring his way.

02:03.360 --> 02:12.920
But the moon shone on his face as he spoke, and the girl was pleased to watch it. It seemed to

02:12.920 --> 02:19.660
be of great disposition, yet with something high, too, as of a well-founded self-esteem.

02:21.000 --> 02:28.140
Presently her eye wandered to the other, and she was surprised to recognize in him a certain Mr.

02:28.520 --> 02:34.420
Hyde, who had once visited her master, and for whom she had conceived a dislike.

02:35.620 --> 02:42.820
He had in his hand a heavy cane with which he was trifling, but he answered never a word.

02:42.920 --> 02:47.020
And seemed to listen with an ill-contained impatience.

02:47.960 --> 02:54.660
And then, all of a sudden, he broke out in a great flame of anger, stamping with his feet,

02:54.980 --> 03:00.980
brandishing the cane, and carrying on, as the maid described it, like a madman.

03:01.720 --> 03:07.500
The old gentleman took a step back, with the air of one very much surprised and a trifle hurt,

03:07.500 --> 03:15.420
and at that Mr. Hyde broke out of all bounds, and clubbed him to the earth. And next moment,

03:15.740 --> 03:22.500
with ape-like fury, he was trampling his victim under foot, and hailing down a storm of blows,

03:23.000 --> 03:28.440
under which the bones were audibly shattered, and the body jumped upon the roadway.

03:29.440 --> 03:33.820
At the horror of these sights and sounds, the maid fainted.

03:35.440 --> 03:42.460
It was two o'clock, when she came to herself, and called the police. The murderer was gone long ago,

03:42.900 --> 03:49.500
but there lay his victim in the middle of the lane, incredibly mangled. The stick with which

03:49.500 --> 03:55.840
the deed had been done, although it was of some rare and very tough and heavy wood, had broken in

03:55.840 --> 04:02.140
the middle under the stress of this insensate cruelty, and one splintered half had rolled into

04:02.140 --> 04:07.460
neighbouring gutter. The other, without doubt, had been carried away by the murderer.

04:08.820 --> 04:16.540
A purse and gold watch were found upon the victim, but no cards or papers, except a sealed and stamped

04:16.540 --> 04:23.140
envelope, which he had been probably carrying to the post, and which bore the name and address

04:23.140 --> 04:30.200
of Mr. Utterson. This was brought to the lawyer the next morning, before he was out of bed,

04:30.200 --> 04:37.020
and he had no sooner seen it and been told the circumstances than he shot out a solemn lip.

04:37.940 --> 04:44.340
I shall say nothing till I have seen the body, said he. This may be very serious.

04:45.080 --> 04:52.040
Have the kindness to wait while I dress. And with the same grave countenance he hurried through his

04:52.040 --> 04:59.120
breakfast and drove to the police station, whither the body had been carried. As soon as he came into

04:59.120 --> 05:01.180
cell, he nodded.

05:01.960 --> 05:10.160
Yes, said he, I recognize him. I am sorry to say that this is Sir Danvers' crew.

05:11.460 --> 05:16.380
Good God, sir! exclaimed the officer. Is it possible?

05:17.720 --> 05:22.080
And the next moment his eye lighted up with professional ambition.

05:23.240 --> 05:29.900
This will make a deal of noise, he said, and perhaps you can help us to the man.

05:31.000 --> 05:37.680
And he briefly narrated what the maid had seen, and showed the broken stick. Mr. Utterson had

05:37.680 --> 05:44.600
already quailed at the name of Hyde, but when the stick was laid before him he could doubt no longer.

05:45.520 --> 05:51.920
Broken and battered as it was, he recognized it for one that he had himself presented many

05:51.920 --> 05:54.820
years before to Henry Jekyll.

05:56.140 --> 06:03.540
Is this Mr. Hyde a person of small stature? he inquired. A particularly small and particularly

06:03.540 --> 06:10.300
wicked looking is what the maid calls him, said the officer. Mr. Utterson reflected,

06:10.880 --> 06:19.660
and then, raising his head, if you will come with me in my cab, he said, I think I can take you to

06:19.660 --> 06:20.520
his house.

06:23.040 --> 06:30.400
It was by this time about nine in the morning, and the first fog of the season. A great chocolate

06:30.400 --> 06:36.220
covered pall lowered over heaven, but the wind was continually charging and routing these

06:36.220 --> 06:42.560
embattled vapors, so that as the cab crawled from street to street, Mr. Utterson beheld a marvelous

06:42.560 --> 06:49.340
number of degrees and hues of twilight. For here it would be dark like the back end of evening,

06:49.660 --> 06:56.180
and there would be a glow of a rich lurid brown like the light of some strange conflagration,

06:56.760 --> 07:03.400
and here, for a moment, the fog would be quite broken up, and a haggard shaft of daylight would

07:03.400 --> 07:11.220
glance in between the swirling wreaths. The dismal quarter of Soho, seen under these changing

07:11.220 --> 07:17.900
glimpses, with its muddy ways and slatternly passengers, and its lamps, which had never been

07:17.900 --> 07:23.060
extinguished or had been kindled afresh to combat this mournful reinvasion of darkness,

07:23.760 --> 07:29.000
seemed, in the lawyer's eyes, like a district of some city in a nightmare.

07:30.060 --> 07:35.880
The thoughts of his mind besides were of the gloomiest dye, and when he glanced at the

07:35.880 --> 07:41.540
companion of his drive, he was conscious of some touch of that terror of the law and the

07:41.540 --> 07:46.080
law's officers, which may at times assail the most honest.

07:47.900 --> 07:54.860
As the cab drew up before the address indicated, the fog lifted a little, and showed him a dingy

07:54.860 --> 08:01.660
street, a gin palace, a low French eating-house, a shop for the retail of penny numbers and

08:01.660 --> 08:08.460
tuppany salads, many ragged children huddled in the doorways, and many women of many different

08:08.460 --> 08:16.260
nationalities passing out, key in hand, to have a morning glass. And the next moment the fog

08:16.260 --> 08:23.460
settled down again upon that part, as brown as umber, and cut him off from his blaggardly

08:23.460 --> 08:32.620
surroundings. This was the home of Henry Jekyll's favourite, of a man who was heir to a quarter of a

08:32.620 --> 08:42.180
million sterling. An ivory-faced and silvery-haired old woman opened the door. She had an evil face,

08:42.180 --> 08:50.400
smoothed by hypocrisy, but her manners were excellent. Yes, she said, this was Mr. Hyde's,

08:50.400 --> 08:56.180
but he was not at home. He had been in that night very late, but he had gone away again

08:56.180 --> 09:01.800
in less than an hour. There was nothing strange in that, his habits were very irregular,

09:02.160 --> 09:09.020
and he was often absent. For instance, it was nearly two months since she had seen him till yesterday.

09:10.340 --> 09:17.240
Very well then, we wish to see his rooms, said the lawyer, and when the woman began to declare

09:17.240 --> 09:26.140
it was impossible, I had better tell you who this person is, he added. This is Inspector Newcomen

09:26.140 --> 09:33.120
of Scotland Yard. A flash of odious joy appeared upon the woman's face.

09:33.120 --> 09:38.980
Ah! said she, he is in trouble. What has he done?

09:40.160 --> 09:43.380
Mr. Utterson and the inspector exchanged glances.

09:44.320 --> 09:50.920
He don't seem a very popular character, observed the latter, and now, my good woman,

09:51.140 --> 09:54.440
just let me and this gentleman have a look about us.

09:55.940 --> 10:01.140
In the whole extent of the house, which but for the old woman remained otherwise empty,

10:01.140 --> 10:07.940
Mr. Hyde had only used a couple of rooms, but these were furnished with luxury and good taste.

10:08.380 --> 10:15.800
A closet was filled with wine, the plate was of silver, the napery elegant, a good picture

10:15.800 --> 10:22.460
hung upon the walls, a gift, as Utterson supposed, from Henry Jekyll, who was much of a connoisseur,

10:22.740 --> 10:26.660
and the carpets were of many plies and agreeable in colour.

10:27.360 --> 10:34.380
At this moment, however, the rooms bore every mark of having been recently and hurriedly ransacked.

10:34.720 --> 10:41.220
Clothes lay about the floor, with their pockets inside out, lock fast drawers stood open, and on

10:41.220 --> 10:48.300
the hearth there lay a pile of grey ashes, as though many papers had been burned. From these

10:48.300 --> 10:54.420
ambers the inspector disinterred the butt-end of a green check-book, which had resisted the action

10:54.420 --> 11:00.720
of the fire. The other half of the stick was found behind the door, and as this clenched

11:00.720 --> 11:08.020
his suspicions, the officer declared himself delighted. A visit to the bank, where several

11:08.020 --> 11:13.440
thousand pounds were found to be lying in the murderer's credit, completed his gratification.

11:14.440 --> 11:18.280
You may depend upon it, sir,' he told Mr. Utterson.

11:18.680 --> 11:24.520
I have him in my hand. He must have lost his head, or he never would have left the stick,

11:24.560 --> 11:29.540
or above all burned the check-book. Why, money's life to the man.

11:29.980 --> 11:35.240
We have nothing to do but wait for him at the bank, and get out the hand-bills.'

11:37.200 --> 11:43.360
This last, however, was not so easy of accomplishment, for Mr. Hyde had numbered few

11:43.360 --> 11:49.400
familiars, even the master of the servant maid had only seen him twice, his family could nowhere

11:49.400 --> 11:55.680
be traced, he had never been photographed, and the few who could describe him differed widely,

11:56.060 --> 12:03.880
as common observers will. Only on one point were they agreed, and that was the haunting sense of

12:03.880 --> 12:08.540
unexpressed deformity with which the fugitive impressed his beholder.

12:12.200 --> 12:13.920
Incident of the Letter

12:15.240 --> 12:21.160
It was late in the afternoon when Mr. Utterson found his way to Dr. Jekyll's door,

12:21.480 --> 12:27.340
where he was at once admitted by Poole, and carried down by the kitchen offices and across

12:27.340 --> 12:32.580
the yard which had once been a garden, to the building that was indifferently known as the

12:32.580 --> 12:38.940
laboratory, or dissecting rooms. The doctor had bought the house from the heirs of a celebrated

12:38.940 --> 12:45.700
surgeon, and his own tastes being rather chemical than anatomical, had changed the destination of

12:45.700 --> 12:51.500
the block at the bottom of the garden. It was the first time that the lawyer had been received in

12:51.500 --> 12:57.500
that part of his friend's quarters, and he eyed the dingy, windowless structure with curiosity,

12:57.500 --> 13:02.740
and gazed round with a distasteful sense of strangeness as he crossed the theatre,

13:03.440 --> 13:10.520
once crowded with eager students, and now lying gaunt and silent, the tables laden with chemical

13:10.520 --> 13:16.040
apparatus, the floor strewn with crates and littered with packing-straw, and the light

13:16.040 --> 13:24.240
falling dimly through the foggy cupola. At the further end a flight of stairs mounted to a door

13:24.240 --> 13:31.060
covered with red bays, and through this Mr. Utterson was at last received into the doctor's

13:31.060 --> 13:38.620
cabinet. It was a large room fitted round with glass presses, furnished, among other things,

13:38.760 --> 13:45.660
with a cheval glass and a business table, and looking out upon the court by three dusty windows

13:45.660 --> 13:52.780
barred with iron. The fire burned in the grate, a lamp was set lighted on the chimney shelf,

13:52.780 --> 14:00.380
for even in the houses the fog began to lie thickly, and there, close up to the warmth,

14:00.880 --> 14:08.040
sat Dr. Jekyll, looking deathly sick. He did not rise to meet his visitor,

14:08.680 --> 14:13.000
but held out a cold hand and bade him welcome in a changed voice.

14:14.300 --> 14:20.580
And now, said Mr. Utterson, as soon as Poole had left them, you have heard the news?

14:21.500 --> 14:22.980
The doctor shuddered.

14:24.160 --> 14:29.720
They were crying it in the square, he said. I heard them in my dining-room.

14:30.840 --> 14:39.560
One word, said the lawyer. Karoo was my client, but so are you, and I want to know what I am doing.

14:40.480 --> 14:43.660
You have not been mad enough to hide this fellow.

14:45.100 --> 14:53.400
Utterson, I swear to God, cried the doctor, I swear to God I will never set eyes on him again.

14:54.120 --> 15:01.560
I bind my honour to you that I am done with him in this world. It is all at an end.

15:02.460 --> 15:10.120
And indeed he does not want my help. You do not know him as I do. He is safe, he is quite safe.

15:10.120 --> 15:14.440
Mark my words, he will never more be heard of.

15:15.660 --> 15:21.460
The lawyer listened gloomily. He did not like his friend's feverish manner.

15:22.180 --> 15:28.480
You seem pretty sure of him, said he, and for your sake I hope you may be right.

15:29.040 --> 15:32.080
If it came to a trial, your name might appear.

15:32.700 --> 15:39.420
I am quite sure of him, replied Jekyll. I have grounds for certainty that

15:39.420 --> 15:45.520
I cannot share with anyone. But there is one thing on which you may advise me.

15:46.020 --> 15:51.680
I have received a letter, and I am at a loss whether I should show it to the police.

15:52.640 --> 15:55.860
I should like to leave it in your hands, Utterson.

15:56.400 --> 16:01.980
You would judge wisely, I am sure. I have so great a trust in you.

16:02.860 --> 16:07.840
You fear, I suppose, that it might lead to his detection? asked the lawyer.

16:08.600 --> 16:16.240
No, said the other, I cannot say that I care what becomes of Hyde. I am quite done with him.

16:16.680 --> 16:22.280
I was thinking of my own character, which this hateful business has rather exposed.

16:23.660 --> 16:28.540
Utterson ruminated awhile. He was surprised at his friend's selfishness,

16:28.700 --> 16:30.880
and yet relieved by it.

16:31.700 --> 16:35.940
Well, said he at last, let me see the letter.

16:36.980 --> 16:44.000
The letter was written in an odd upright hand, and signed Edward Hyde, and it signified,

16:44.400 --> 16:50.820
briefly enough, that the writer's benefactor, Dr. Jekyll, whom he had long so unworthily

16:50.820 --> 16:56.760
repaid for a thousand generosities, need labour under no alarm for his safety,

16:57.280 --> 17:01.540
as he had means of escape on which he placed a sure dependence.

17:02.320 --> 17:08.940
The lawyer liked this letter well enough. It put a better colour on the intimacy than he had looked

17:08.940 --> 17:13.500
for, and he blamed himself for some of his past suspicions.

17:14.200 --> 17:16.900
Have you the envelope? he asked.

17:18.040 --> 17:23.320
I burned it, replied Jekyll, before I thought what I was about.

17:24.240 --> 17:28.280
But it bore no postmark. The note was handed in.

17:28.990 --> 17:33.000
Shall I keep this and sleep upon it? asked Utterson.

17:33.980 --> 17:41.580
I wish you to judge for me entirely, was the reply. I have lost confidence in myself.

17:43.260 --> 17:50.440
Well, I shall consider, returned the lawyer. And now one word more.

17:50.940 --> 17:55.480
It was Hyde who dictated the terms in your will about that disappearance?

17:56.200 --> 18:03.300
The doctor seemed seized with a qualm of faintness. He shut his mouth tight and nodded.

18:04.360 --> 18:11.100
I knew it, said Utterson. He meant to murder you. You had a fine escape.

18:11.980 --> 18:17.040
I have had what is far more to the purpose, returned the doctor solemnly.

18:17.420 --> 18:23.980
I have had a lesson. O God, Utterson, what a lesson I have had!

18:24.580 --> 18:28.120
And he covered his face for a moment with his hands.

18:29.700 --> 18:33.980
On his way out, the lawyer stopped and had a word or two with Poole.

18:34.800 --> 18:41.580
By the by, said he. There was a letter handed in to-day. What was the messenger like?

18:42.480 --> 18:46.120
But Poole was positive nothing had come except by post.

18:46.900 --> 18:49.860
At only circulars by that, he added.

18:51.220 --> 18:58.440
This news sent off the visitor with his fears renewed. Plainly, the letter had come by the

18:58.440 --> 19:05.180
laboratory door. Possibly, indeed, it had been written in the cabinet. And if that were so,

19:05.300 --> 19:09.640
it must be differently judged, and handled with the more caution.

19:10.800 --> 19:15.640
The newsboys, as he went, were crying themselves hoarse along the footways.

19:16.200 --> 19:20.240
Special edition! Shocking murder of an MP!

19:21.640 --> 19:28.020
That was the funeral oration of one friend and client, and he could not help a certain

19:28.020 --> 19:33.540
apprehension lest the good name of another should be sucked down in the eddy of the scandal.

19:34.760 --> 19:41.740
It was, at last, a ticklish decision that he had to make, and self-reliant as he was by habit,

19:41.740 --> 19:48.020
he began to cherish a longing for advice. It was not to be had directly,

19:48.560 --> 19:52.180
but perhaps, he thought, it might be fished for.

19:53.900 --> 20:00.200
Presently after, he sat on one side of his own hearth, with Mr. Guest, his head clerk,

20:00.220 --> 20:05.660
upon the other, and midway between, at a nicely calculated distance from the fire,

20:05.660 --> 20:12.760
a bottle of a particular old wine that had long dwelt unsund in the foundation of his house.

20:13.900 --> 20:20.700
The fog still slept on the wing above the drowned city, where the lamps glimmered like carbuncles,

20:21.080 --> 20:27.280
and through the muffle and smother of these fallen clouds, the procession of the town's life was

20:27.280 --> 20:34.860
still rolling in through the great arteries with a sound as of a mighty wind. But the room was

20:34.860 --> 20:42.000
with firelight. In the bottle, the acids were long ago resolved, the imperial dye had softened with

20:42.000 --> 20:48.500
time, as the colour grows richer in stained windows, and the glow of hot autumn afternoons

20:48.500 --> 20:53.980
on hillside vineyards was ready to be set free and disperse the fogs of London.

20:55.840 --> 21:02.720
Insensibly, the lawyer melted. There was no man from whom he kept fewer secrets than Mr. Guest,

21:02.720 --> 21:09.380
and he was not always sure that he kept as many as he meant. Guest had often been on business to

21:09.380 --> 21:15.640
the doctors, a new pool, he could scarce have failed to hear of Mr. Hyde's familiarity about

21:15.640 --> 21:23.160
the house. He might draw conclusions. Was it not as well, then, that he should see a letter which

21:23.160 --> 21:29.610
put that mystery to right? And above all, since Guest, being a great student and critic of

21:29.610 --> 21:36.510
would consider the step natural and obliging. The clerk, besides, was a man of counsel.

21:37.050 --> 21:43.910
He could scarce read so strange a document without dropping a remark, and by that remark

21:43.910 --> 21:51.730
Mr. Utterson might shape his future course. This is a sad business about Sir Danvers, he said.

21:52.470 --> 21:57.510
Yes, sir, indeed. It has elicited a great deal of public feeling,

21:57.990 --> 22:01.350
returned Guest. The man, of course, was mad.

22:02.210 --> 22:08.750
I should like to hear your views on that, replied Utterson. I have a document here in his

22:08.750 --> 22:16.090
handwriting. It is between ourselves, for I scarce know what to do about it. It is an ugly

22:16.090 --> 22:23.050
business at the best, but there it is, quite in your way, a murderer's autograph.

22:24.790 --> 22:29.390
Guest's eyes brightened, and he sat down at once and studied it with passion.

22:30.610 --> 22:39.630
No, sir, he said, not mad, but it is an odd hand. And by all accounts a very odd writer,

22:39.630 --> 22:44.130
added the lawyer. Just then the servant entered with a note.

22:45.170 --> 22:51.270
Is that from Dr. Jekyll, sir? inquired the clerk. I thought I knew the writing.

22:52.450 --> 22:54.610
Anything private, Mr. Utterson?

22:55.930 --> 23:00.810
Only an invitation to dinner. Why? Do you want to see it?

23:01.550 --> 23:07.710
One moment, I thank you, sir. And the clerk laid the two sheets of paper alongside,

23:07.710 --> 23:10.350
and sedulously compared their contents.

23:11.710 --> 23:19.090
Thank you, sir, he said at last, returning both. It's a very interesting autograph.

23:20.390 --> 23:24.770
There was a pause, during which Mr. Utterson struggled with himself.

23:26.010 --> 23:30.090
Why did you compare them, Guest? he inquired suddenly.

23:31.040 --> 23:36.270
Well, sir, returned the clerk, there's a rather singular resemblance.

23:36.790 --> 23:41.160
The two hands are in many points identical, only differently sloped.

23:43.370 --> 23:50.470
Rather quaint, said Utterson. It is, as you say, rather quaint, returned Guest.

23:51.790 --> 23:56.190
I wouldn't speak of this note, you know, said the master.

23:57.050 --> 24:01.330
No, sir, said the clerk. I understand.

24:04.250 --> 24:08.170
But no sooner was Mr. Utterson alone that night,

24:08.310 --> 24:13.490
than he locked the note into his safe, where it reposed from that time forward.

24:14.770 --> 24:23.370
What? he thought. Henry Jekyll forged for a murderer, and his blood ran cold in his veins.

24:28.250 --> 24:30.130
Incident of Dr. Lanyon

24:32.070 --> 24:38.650
Time ran on. Thousands of pounds were offered in reward, for the death of Sir Danvers was

24:38.650 --> 24:45.190
resented as a public injury. But Mr. Hyde had disappeared out of the ken of the police,

24:45.330 --> 24:51.950
as though he had never existed. Much of his past was unearthed, indeed, and all disreputable.

24:51.950 --> 24:58.690
Tales came out of the man's cruelty, at once so callous and violent, of his vile life,

24:58.770 --> 25:04.110
of his strange associates, of the hatred that seemed to have surrounded his career,

25:04.830 --> 25:11.870
but of his present whereabouts not a whisper. From the time he had left his house in Soho,

25:12.010 --> 25:18.710
on the morning of the murder, he was simply blotted out, and gradually, as time drew on,

25:18.710 --> 25:25.450
Mr. Utterson began to recover from the hotness of his alarm, and to grow more at quiet with

25:25.450 --> 25:32.830
himself. The death of Sir Danvers was, to his way of thinking, more than paid for by the

25:32.830 --> 25:40.250
disappearance of Mr. Hyde. Now that that evil influence had been withdrawn, a new life began

25:40.250 --> 25:47.510
for Dr. Jekyll. He came out of his seclusion, renewed relations with his friends, became once

25:47.510 --> 25:53.190
their familiar guest and entertainer, and whilst he had always been known for charities,

25:53.650 --> 26:01.050
he was now no less distinguished for religion. He was busy, he was much in the open air,

26:01.390 --> 26:08.490
he did good, his face seemed to open and brighten, as if with an inward consciousness of service,

26:08.910 --> 26:13.390
and for more than two months the doctor was at peace.

26:15.030 --> 26:21.950
On the eighth of January Utterson had dined at the doctor's with a small party. Lanyon had been

26:21.950 --> 26:27.390
there, and the face of the host had looked from one to the other as in the old days,

26:27.410 --> 26:33.390
when the trio were inseparable friends. On the twelfth and again on the fourteenth,

26:33.910 --> 26:36.190
the door was shut against the lawyer.

26:37.070 --> 26:43.210
The doctor was confined to the house, Poole said, and saw no one.

26:44.510 --> 26:50.950
On the fifteenth he tried again, and was again refused, and having now been used for the last

26:50.950 --> 26:57.230
two months to see his friend almost daily, he found this return of solitude to weigh upon

26:57.230 --> 27:04.670
his spirits. The fifth night he had ingest to dine with him, and the sixth he betook himself

27:04.670 --> 27:13.390
to Dr. Lanyon. There at least he was not denied admittance, but when he came in he was shocked

27:13.390 --> 27:19.150
at the change which had taken place in the doctor's appearance. He had his death warrant

27:19.150 --> 27:25.850
written legibly upon his face. The rosy man had grown pale, his flesh had fallen away,

27:26.250 --> 27:33.570
he was visibly bolder and older, and yet it was not so much these tokens of a swift physical

27:33.570 --> 27:40.090
decay that arrested the lawyer's notice, as a look in the eye and quality of manner that

27:40.090 --> 27:47.250
seemed to testify to some deep-seated terror of the mind. It was unlikely that the doctor

27:47.250 --> 27:52.250
should fear death, and yet that was what Utterson was tempted to suspect.

27:53.510 --> 28:01.770
Yes, he thought, he is a doctor, he must know his own state, and that his days are counted,

28:02.290 --> 28:09.470
and the knowledge is more than he can bear. And yet, when Utterson remarked on his ill looks,

28:10.050 --> 28:15.910
it was with an air of great firmness that Lanyon declared himself a doomed man.

28:17.610 --> 28:24.830
I have had a shock, he said, and I shall never recover. It is a question of weeks.

28:25.890 --> 28:32.270
Well, life has been pleasant. I liked it. Yes, sir, I used to like it.

28:32.550 --> 28:36.530
I sometimes think if we knew all, we should be more glad to get away.

28:38.170 --> 28:41.910
Jekyll is ill too, observed Utterson. Have you seen him?

28:43.250 --> 28:47.310
But Lanyon's face changed, and he held up a trembling hand.

28:47.310 --> 28:53.830
I wish to see or hear no more of Dr. Jekyll, he said in a loud,

28:54.290 --> 28:57.790
unsteady voice. I am quite done with that person,

28:58.150 --> 29:04.070
and I beg that you will spare me any allusion to one whom I regard as dead.

29:05.250 --> 29:10.930
Tut, tut, said Mr. Utterson, and then, after a considerable pause,

29:11.570 --> 29:17.830
Can't I do anything? he inquired. We are three very old friends, Lanyon.

29:18.310 --> 29:20.530
We shall not live to make others.

29:21.490 --> 29:25.710
Nothing can be done, returned Lanyon. Ask himself.

29:26.650 --> 29:29.150
He will not see me, said the lawyer.

29:30.110 --> 29:37.670
I am not surprised at that, was the reply. Someday, Utterson, after I am dead,

29:37.670 --> 29:43.750
you may perhaps come to learn the right and wrong of this. I cannot tell you.

29:44.190 --> 29:48.230
And in the meantime, if you can sit and talk with me of other things,

29:48.450 --> 29:54.470
for God's sake stay and do so. But if you cannot keep clear of this accursed topic,

29:54.970 --> 29:59.190
then in God's name go, for I cannot bear it.

30:00.710 --> 30:06.770
As soon as he got home, Utterson sat down and wrote to Jekyll, complaining of his exclusion

30:06.770 --> 30:11.030
from the house, and asking the cause of this unhappy break with Lanyon.

30:11.710 --> 30:16.910
And the next day brought him a long answer, often very pathetically worded,

30:17.070 --> 30:23.750
and sometimes darkly mysterious in drift. The quarrel with Lanyon was incurable.

30:24.170 --> 30:31.930
I do not blame our old friend, Jekyll wrote, but I share his view that we must never meet.

30:32.490 --> 30:36.910
I mean from henceforth to lead a life of extreme seclusion.

30:37.670 --> 30:41.850
You must not be surprised, nor must you doubt my friendship,

30:42.290 --> 30:49.810
if my door is often shut, even to you. You must suffer me to go my own dark way.

30:50.410 --> 30:56.090
I have brought on myself a punishment and a danger that I cannot name.

30:57.030 --> 31:03.050
If I am the chief of sinners, I am the chief of sufferers also.

31:03.910 --> 31:10.690
I could not think that this earth contained a place for sufferings and terrors so unmanning.

31:11.210 --> 31:19.770
And you can do but one thing, Utterson, to lighten this destiny, and that is to respect my silence.

31:21.210 --> 31:25.910
Utterson was amazed. The dark influence of Hyde had been withdrawn.

31:26.370 --> 31:33.010
The doctor had returned to his old tasks and amities. A week ago the prospect had smiled with

31:33.010 --> 31:40.710
every promise of a cheerful and an honoured age, and now, in a moment, friendship and peace of mind

31:40.710 --> 31:48.210
and the whole tenor of his life were wrecked. So great and unprepared a change pointed to madness,

31:48.210 --> 31:54.830
but in view of Lanyon's words and manner, there must lie for it some deeper ground.

31:56.470 --> 32:03.990
A week afterwards Dr. Lanyon took to his bed, and in something less than a fortnight he was dead.

32:04.690 --> 32:11.810
The night after the funeral, at which he had been sadly affected, Utterson locked the door of his

32:11.810 --> 32:18.190
business room, and sitting there by the light of a melancholy candle, drew out and set before him

32:18.190 --> 32:23.970
an envelope, addressed by the hand, and sealed with the seal of his dear friend.

32:25.030 --> 32:33.030
Private for the hands of J.G. Utterson alone, and in the case of his predecease to be destroyed

32:33.030 --> 32:40.750
unread. So it was emphatically superscribed, and the lawyer dreaded to behold the contents.

32:41.590 --> 32:48.470
I have buried one friend today, he thought. What if this should cost me another?

32:49.410 --> 32:57.010
And then he condemned the fear as a disloyalty, and broke the seal. Within there was another

32:57.010 --> 33:04.050
enclosure, likewise sealed, and marked upon the cover as not to be opened till the death or

33:04.050 --> 33:06.170
disappearance of Dr. Henry Jekyll.

33:07.350 --> 33:14.510
Utterson could not trust his eyes. Yes, it was disappearance. Here again,

33:14.670 --> 33:21.050
as in the mad will which he had long ago restored to its author, here again were the idea of a

33:21.050 --> 33:27.770
disappearance in the name of Henry Jekyll bracketed. But in the will, that idea had sprung from the

33:28.330 --> 33:34.670
suggestion of the man Hyde. It was set there with a purpose all too plain and horrible.

33:35.450 --> 33:42.490
Written by the hand of Lanyon, what should it mean? A great curiosity came on the trustee

33:42.490 --> 33:47.910
to disregard the prohibition, and dive at once to the bottom of these mysteries.

33:48.630 --> 33:55.550
The professional honor and faith of his dead friend were stringent obligations, and the packet

33:55.550 --> 34:03.410
slept in the inmost corner of his private safe. It is one thing to mortify curiosity,

34:04.210 --> 34:10.970
another to conquer it. And it may be doubted if, from that day forth, Utterson desired the

34:10.970 --> 34:16.090
society of his surviving friend with the same eagerness. He thought of him kindly,

34:16.570 --> 34:24.110
but his thoughts were disquieted and fearful. He went to call indeed, but he was perhaps relieved

34:24.110 --> 34:30.290
to be denied admittance. Perhaps, in his heart, he preferred to speak with Poole about the doorstep,

34:30.690 --> 34:36.010
and surrounded by the air and sounds of the open city, rather than to be admitted into the

34:36.010 --> 34:41.770
house of voluntary bondage, and to sit and speak with its inscrutable recluse.

34:42.810 --> 34:48.910
Poole had indeed no very pleasant news to communicate. The doctor, it appeared,

34:48.910 --> 34:53.910
now more than ever, confined himself to the cabinet over the laboratory,

34:54.370 --> 35:00.170
where he would sometimes even sleep. He was out of spirits, he had grown very silent,

35:00.510 --> 35:08.150
he did not read. It seemed as if he had something on his mind. Utterson became so used to the

35:08.150 --> 35:14.770
unvarying character of these reports, that he fell off little by little in the frequency of his visit.

35:18.650 --> 35:20.550
Incidents at the Window

35:21.690 --> 35:27.210
It chanced on Sunday, when Mr. Utterson was on his usual walk with Mr. Enfield,

35:27.730 --> 35:33.070
that their way lay once again through the by-street, and that when they came in front of

35:33.070 --> 35:35.950
the door both stopped to gaze on it.

35:37.330 --> 35:44.610
"'Well,' said Enfield, "'that story's an end at least. We shall never see more of Mr. Hyde.'

35:44.610 --> 35:47.010
"'I hope not,' said Utterson.

35:47.590 --> 35:51.790
"'Did I ever tell you that I once saw him and shared your feeling of repulsion?'

35:52.410 --> 35:56.930
"'It was impossible to do one without the other,' returned Enfield.

35:57.310 --> 36:03.170
"'And by the way, what an ass you must have thought of me not to know that this was a back

36:03.170 --> 36:09.300
way to Dr. Jekyll's. It was partly your own fault that I found it out, even when I did.'

36:10.170 --> 36:13.790
"'So you found it out, did you?' said Utterson.

36:14.250 --> 36:19.090
"'But if that be so, we may step into the court and take a look at the windows.

36:19.550 --> 36:23.570
"'To tell you the truth, I am uneasy about poor Jekyll,

36:24.090 --> 36:29.140
and even outside I feel as if the presence of a friend might do him good.'

36:30.160 --> 36:37.200
"'The court was very cool and a little damp, and full of premature twilight, although the sky,

36:37.500 --> 36:44.500
high up overhead, was still bright with sunset. The middle of one of the three windows was halfway

36:44.500 --> 36:50.520
open, and sitting close beside it, taking the air with an infinite sadness of mean,

36:50.940 --> 36:55.480
like some disconsolate prisoner, Utterson saw Dr. Jekyll.

36:56.240 --> 37:00.560
"'What, Jekyll?' he cried. "'I trust you are better?'

37:01.240 --> 37:06.280
"'I am very low, Utterson,' replied the doctor drearily.

37:06.820 --> 37:11.540
"'Very low. It will not last long, thank God.'

37:12.780 --> 37:16.140
"'You stay too much indoors,' said the lawyer.

37:16.300 --> 37:20.940
"'You should be out whipping up the circulation like Mr. Enfield and me.

37:21.580 --> 37:25.240
This is my cousin, Mr. Enfield, Dr. Jekyll.

37:25.940 --> 37:29.860
Come now, get your hat, and take a quick turn with us.'

37:30.740 --> 37:33.760
"'You are very good,' sighed the other.

37:33.940 --> 37:42.880
"'I should like to very much. But no, no, no, it is quite impossible. I dare not.'

37:44.220 --> 37:50.160
"'But indeed, Utterson, I am very glad to see you. This is really a great pleasure.'

37:50.940 --> 37:56.400
"'I would ask you and Mr. Enfield up, but the place is really not fit.'

37:57.200 --> 38:00.140
"'Why then?' said the lawyer good-naturedly.

38:00.140 --> 38:04.680
"'The best thing we can do is to stay down here and speak with you from where we are.'

38:05.460 --> 38:12.080
"'That is just what I was about to venture to propose,' returned the doctor with a smile.

38:12.920 --> 38:18.200
But the words were hardly uttered before the smile was struck out of his face,

38:18.200 --> 38:22.500
and succeeded by an expression of such abject terror and despair

38:22.500 --> 38:26.500
as froze the very blood of the two gentlemen below.

38:27.500 --> 38:32.440
They saw it but for a glimpse, for the window was instantly thrust down,

38:33.140 --> 38:39.280
but that glimpse had been sufficient, and they turned and left the court without a word.

38:40.620 --> 38:46.680
In silence too they traversed the by-street, and it was not until they had come into a

38:46.680 --> 38:52.340
thoroughfare, where even upon a Sunday there were still some stirrings of life,

38:52.920 --> 38:57.040
that Mr. Utterson at last turned and looked at his companion.

38:58.140 --> 39:02.840
They were both pale, and there was an answering horror in their eyes.

39:04.080 --> 39:10.420
"'God forgive us! God forgive us!' said Mr. Utterson.

39:10.420 --> 39:19.220
But Mr. Enfield only nodded his head very seriously, and walked on once more in silence.

